The number increased steadily over the next few years, reaching its peak in 2013 with 395 thousand marriages. Afterward, there was a decline, with numbers dropping to 330 thousand in 2018 and further to 285 thousand in 2020.

The bar chart illustrates the share of Canadians' willingness to get vaccinated for COVID-19 across different time periods from July 2020 to March 2021. It shows four categories: those who would get vaccinated as soon as one became available, those who would eventually but wait first, those who would not get vaccinated, and those unsure. The percentages vary over time, with the highest willingness to vaccinate peaking at 65% in March 2021, while the lowest was 46% in July 2020. The 'No' category fluctuates between 12% and 14%, and the 'Not sure' category ranges from 7% to 9%.

The histogram illustrates public opinion on various measures to fight COVID-19 in Great Britain as of October 2020. It shows the percentage of individuals who believe each measure would be effective in reducing the spread of the virus. The measures include having people work from home, encouraging people to wear masks, closing schools and universities, limiting gatherings, testing and tracing, providing free testing, isolating those with symptoms, closing pubs and restaurants, cancelling non-essential travel, and having local curfews. The percentages range from 85% for working from home to 30% for local curfews.

The line chart illustrates the export value of agriculture, hunting, and fishery products from Algeria over six years, from 2014 to 2019. The data shows an increasing trend in export values, starting at 3000 million Algerian dinars in 2014 and rising to 12000 million dinars by 2019. Each year marks a consistent increase in the export value, with notable jumps such as from 6000 to 8500 million dinars between 2016 and 2017.

The histogram illustrates the production value of leading agricultural products in Algeria for 2018, measured in million U.S. dollars. Dates lead with a value of $3700 million, followed by cereals at $1950 million, and potatoes at $1750 million. Oranges have a production value of $1200 million, while apples stand at $880 million. Grapes, tomatoes, watermelons, garlic, green chillies, and dry onions follow, with values ranging from $450 to $350 million.

The histogram illustrates the extent to which people in Hungary followed COVID-19-related news in 2020. It shows four categories: "More than other types of news" with 58%, "To the same extent as other types of news" at 17%, "I do not follow COVID-19 related news" at 19%, and "I do not follow news at all" at 6%.

The bar chart illustrates the percentage of the population with insufficient physical activity across selected countries in Latin America between 2001 and 2016. Brazil shows a rate of 48%, Costa Rica at 47%, Argentina at 41%, Colombia at 36%, Ecuador at 27%, Chile at 26%, and Uruguay at 22%. The data suggests a range of physical activity levels among these countries during the specified period.

The histogram illustrates the number of deaths in the shipbuilding industry in South Korea from 2015 to 2019, categorized by work experience. New hires with less than 6 months of experience account for 32 deaths. Those with 6 months to 1 year of experience have 16 deaths recorded. The group with 1 to 5 years of experience shows 28 fatalities. Lastly, employees with more than 5 years of experience have 9 deaths reported.

The histogram illustrates the travel destinations of Romanian nationals who tested positive for COVID-19 from February to March 2020, by country. Italy leads with 35 cases, followed by The UK and Israel with 3 and 2 cases respectively. Germany, Austria, and the USA each had 2 cases, while France, United Arab Emirates, and Belgium reported 1 case each.

The line chart illustrates real GDP growth in Romania for the years 2020 and 2021, presented under two different scenarios: single-hit and double-hit. In the single-hit scenario, the GDP growth is projected to improve from -5% in 2020 to 4.5% in 2021. Conversely, the double-hit scenario shows a more severe decline starting at -7% in 2020, with an expected recovery to 1.9% by 2021. The data points represent annual changes in percentage terms.

The line chart illustrates the growth in direct jobs created by the app economy within the European Union from January 2016 to July 2019. The data points show an increase over time, starting at 520 thousand jobs in January 2016 and reaching 670 thousand jobs by July 2019. Each subsequent year marks a rise in the number of jobs, with a notable jump from 520 thousand in 2016 to 600 thousand in 2017, followed by consistent growth each year until reaching 670 thousand in 2019.

The bar chart illustrates the Consumer Price Index (CPI) for various food and non-alcoholic beverage subgroups in Ghana from August 2019 to April 2021. The CPI values range from 102 for fruit, vegetables, tubers, plantains, and root crops to 137 for milk, other dairy products, and cheese. Other categories include bread and cereals at 132, meat and poultry at 125, eggs at 120, fish and seafood at 118, sugar, tea, coffee, and cocoa at 116, and vegetable juice at 102.

The line chart illustrates the unemployment rates in Algeria from 2010 to 2019, distinguishing between females and males. In 2010, the female unemployment rate was 18.5% compared to 8.1% for males. Over the years, there is a fluctuating trend with peaks and troughs; for instance, in 2016, the female rate rose to 20.2%, while male unemployment dipped to 8.0%. The data shows that female unemployment generally fluctuates more than male unemployment over this period.

The histogram illustrates the distribution of Hungarians by who they buy Christmas gifts for in 2020. It shows that 95 individuals bought presents for close family members, 23 for friends, 20 for extended family, and 7 for colleagues.

The bar chart illustrates the opinions of U.S. adults in 2020 regarding various statements about e-cigarettes. It shows the percentage of respondents who strongly disagreed, somewhat disagreed, somewhat agreed, and strongly agreed with each statement. For instance, 8% strongly disagreed that e-cigarettes have health effects similar to traditional cigarettes, while 58% strongly agreed. The chart covers topics such as e-cigarettes being a gateway for youth, their potential to reduce smoking, their use as an alternative to smoking, their impact on public health, and their flavor appeal.

The bar chart illustrates the global confidence levels in business ability to understand cyber threats in 2019, segmented by industry type. Manufacturing businesses show a distribution of 21% highly confident, 58% fairly confident, and 21% not at all confident. All other industries report slightly higher percentages for both highly confident (23%) and not at all confident (17%), with a majority (60%) feeling fairly confident.

The histogram illustrates the distribution of requests to delist website content from Google in Denmark, categorized by reason, from 2016 to 2020. Requests are segmented into various categories: 'Insufficient information' leads with 23 requests, followed by 'Name not found' at 21 requests. 'Professional information' and 'Miscellaneous' follow with 16 and 13 requests respectively. 'Other' reasons account for 9 requests, while 'Self authored' content has 8 requests. The least common reasons include 'Crime' and 'Personal information', each with 6 requests.

The line chart illustrates the volume of French imports and exports of used textile articles and rags from 2015 to 2019. In 2015, exports were at 1,500,000 units with imports at 200,000 units. There is an upward trend in both exports and imports over the years, with exports peaking at 1,900,000 units in 2018 before slightly decreasing to 1,750,000 units in 2019. Imports also show growth, reaching 240,000 units by 2018, followed by a slight decrease to 230,000 units in 2019.

The line chart illustrates the number of clinical trial starts for novel heart failure drugs in the U.S. from 2009 to 2018, categorized by stage. In 2009, there were 2 Phase I, 5 Phase II, and 4 Phase III trials. The following years show fluctuations with peaks at 6 Phase I, 7 Phase II, and 10 Phase III trials in 2011, and a high of 7 Phase I, 13 Phase II, and 10 Phase III trials in 2018. The data points for each year indicate the progression or decline of clinical trials across these three stages.

The bar chart illustrates the sales growth of hygiene and household products in Argentina during the period from February 24 to March 1, and from March 2 to March 8, likely due to the impact of COVID-19. Antiseptics saw an increase from 310 units to 370 units, household insecticides from 140 units to 260 units, and toilet soaps from 55 units to 85 units within these respective time frames.

The line chart illustrates the growth in registered mobile money customers in Uganda from 2015 to 2021. Starting at 15 million in 2015, the number of customers increased steadily each year, reaching 32.4 million by 2020. There was a slight dip in 2021, with the customer count dropping to 31.8 million. The data points for each year are plotted on the chart, showing the trend over this seven-year period.

The bar chart illustrates online search trends for "The Queen's Gambit" in Mexico during various weeks of 2020. The data shows searches peaked at 100 on November 1-7, with subsequent weeks fluctuating between 65 and 98. Searches were also conducted using the Spanish terms "Gambito de Dama" and "Gambito," with the highest number of searches being 100 for both terms on November 15-21. The lowest searches for these terms occurred on October 18-24, with 30 and 7 respectively.

The line chart illustrates the trend in proved natural gas reserves in Angola from 2016 to 2020, measured in billion cubic metrics. In 2016, the reserves were at 440 billion cubic metrics, which then decreased each year, reaching 300 billion cubic metrics by 2020. The data points for subsequent years show a consistent decline: 430 billion in 2017, 420 billion in 2018, 400 billion in 2019, and 350 billion in 2020.

The line chart illustrates the natural gas demand in Angola from 2016 to 2020, measured in million cubic meters. In 2016, the demand was at 770 million cubic meters, which increased steadily each year, reaching 780 million cubic meters in 2017, 790 million in 2018, 800 million in 2019, and peaking at 820 million cubic meters in 2020.

The histogram illustrates the number of foreign students enrolled in higher education degrees at university institutions in Spain during the academic year 2019/2020, categorized by their origin. European Union-28 countries lead with 33,500 students, followed by Latin America and Caribbean with 17,000. Asia and Oceania have 8,000 students, North Africa has 6,000, while the Rest of Africa accounts for 1,500. The United States and Canada host 800 students, and the Rest of Europe has 800 as well.

The line chart illustrates the number of employees at Shin-Etsu Chemical Co., Ltd. over a span of ten years, from fiscal year 2011 to 2020. The data shows an increase in employee numbers, starting from 16,000 in 2011 and rising steadily each year, reaching 24,000 by 2020. Each year marks a consistent growth in the workforce, with no significant dips or fluctuations observed during this period.

The histogram illustrates the leading internet activities among young people in Norway for 2020. Activities include instant messaging (98%), participating in social networks (97%), listening to music (96%), watching video content from sharing services (95%), web browsing (94%), watching movies or series from streaming services (93%), reading news online (92%), finding information about goods and services (91%), making video calls (90%), and banking online (88%).

The bar chart illustrates the foreign population in selected European countries over three different years: 1960, 1976, and 1990. In 1960, France had 2500 foreigners, Germany had 3000, Italy had 2000, Spain had 1500, and the UK had 2000. By 1976, these numbers increased to 3000 for France, 4000 for Germany, 2500 for Italy, 2000 for Spain, and 3000 for the UK. In 1990, the figures further rose to 3500 for France, 5000 for Germany, 3000 for Italy, 2500 for Spain, and 4000 for the UK.

The histogram illustrates the change in time spent on PC gaming by genre among U.S. gamers during the COVID-19 pandemic, as of June 2020. The data shows an increase in time for Fighting games by 25%, Battle Royal by 20%, Multiplayer Online Battle Arena by 15%, and Rhythm games by 10%. Simulation games saw a 5% increase, while Shooter and Action-Adventure games had smaller increases at 3% and 2%, respectively. RPGs, Sports, and Strategy/Puzzle genres experienced decreases of 10%, 15%, and 30%, respectively.

The histogram illustrates the impact of the COVID-19 pandemic on cosmetics exports in Poland during 2020. It shows five categories: "Stopped exporting," "Export level/value increased," "Export level/value decreased," "No change to company's export," and "Developed exports/new markets." The values for each category are represented as percentages, with "Stopped exporting" at 7%, "Increased" at 48%, "Decreased" at 19%, "No change" at 15%, and "Developed exports/new markets" at 13%.

The bar chart illustrates the number of coronavirus (COVID-19) cases per 100 thousand people in Estonia over a period from 2020 to 2022, broken down by region. Lääne maakond leads with 4600 cases, followed by Harju maakond at 4200, and Tartu maakond at 3800. The lowest number of cases is reported in Ida-Viru maakond with 1600 cases. Other regions fall between these extremes, with Pärnu maakond showing 3200 cases, and Viru maakond having 2300 cases. The data spans multiple years, indicating a trend or snapshot of the pandemic's impact across Estonia's regions.

The line chart illustrates the trend of private consumption as a percentage of Vietnam's total GDP from 2012 to 2020. In 2012, private consumption was at 64.5% of GDP, which increased steadily each year, reaching 68.5% in 2016. Thereafter, it fluctuated, dipping to 67.5% in 2018 before rising again to 68.2% in 2019 and further to 68.4% in 2020.

The bar chart illustrates public opinion on two COVID-19-related measures in Russia for 2020. It shows the percentage of people who rather support or do not support each measure. For mandatory mask-wearing in public places, 90% support and 10% oppose. Regarding a distance requirement of 1.5-2 meters between people in public places, 88% support it, while 12% do not.

The line chart illustrates the trend in average retail prices of wheat flour in Russia from 2017 to 2020, measured in Russian rubles per kilogram. The data points show an increase over the years: starting at 32 rubles in 2017, the price rose to 33 in 2018, then to 35 in 2019, and finally reached 39 rubles by 2020. Each year marks a consistent rise in the cost of wheat flour.

The bar chart illustrates public opinion in Russia regarding returning to pre-perestroika times over various months from 1995 to 2020. It shows three categories: 'Agree', 'Disagree', and 'Difficult to answer'. In October 1995, 53 people agreed, 35 disagreed, and 14 were unsure. By February 2008, the number of those who agreed decreased to 31, while those who disagreed increased to 52, with 17 undecided. The data points for each month show fluctuations in these opinions, with the 'Difficult to answer' category generally increasing over time, peaking at 25% in March 2015.

The line chart illustrates the vaccination rates for influenza among U.S. white and black adults aged 65 and older from 2009 to 2018. In 2009, 67% of whites and 52% of blacks were vaccinated. The vaccination rate for whites peaked in 2010 at 75%, while that for blacks reached its highest in 2010 at 63%. Over the years, fluctuations occurred with the highest white vaccination rate in 2014 at 70% and the highest black rate also in 2010 at 63%. By 2018, the vaccination rate for whites was 69%, and for blacks, it was 59%.

The bar chart illustrates the impact of COVID-19 on caregivers' responsibilities in the United States, as of September 2020. It shows three categories: overall changes, financial hardship, and no financial hardship. For overall changes, 36% increased, 54% stayed about the same, and 10% decreased. In terms of financial hardship, 42% increased, 47% stayed the same, and 11% decreased. Those without financial hardship experienced an increase in 25%, stability in 42%, and a decrease in 33%.

The histogram illustrates the reasons for cyber stalking ex or current partners online according to U.S. adults in 2019. The reasons are categorized as follows: 'Just curious' with a value of 38, 'Did not trust their ex or current partner or suspected they were doing the same' with a value of 45, and 'To find out if their ex or current partner was checking in on them, so decided to do the same' with a value of 20.

The histogram illustrates the growth in clicks for various product categories during Black Friday 2019, compared to an average Friday. Consoles lead with a 1530 increase in clicks, followed by headphones at 897, wireless speakers at 812, televisions at 665, and soundbars at 604.

The histogram illustrates reasons why French individuals were more advanced in Christmas gift shopping and preparation in 2020 compared to the same period last year. The reasons include making purchases before Black Friday, taking advantage of early sales, being ahead of the December rush, buying more time with containment measures, and adapting to help retailers by buying earlier. The number of responses for each reason is represented as percentages: 45% for 'I made my purchases before Black Friday', 34% for 'Sales will begin in September', 30% for 'I am ahead of the rush in December', 26% for 'I bought more time with containment', and 15% for 'I adapted to help the retailers'.

The bar chart illustrates the forecasted electricity generation in France for the year 2050, broken down by energy source and measured in terawatt hours (TWh). Nuclear power is projected to generate 185 TWh, while onshore wind will contribute 153 TWh. Solar energy is expected to produce 86 TWh, with offshore wind at 74 TWh. Other renewables are forecasted to generate 75 TWh, combined cycle gas turbines (CCGT) at 23 TWh, hydroelectric power at 15 TWh, and gas peaking at 9 TWh. Battery storage and pumped storage are anticipated to generate 0.5 and 0.3 TWh respectively.
